15 ESLint rules behave differently from their TSLint counterparts:
  * arrow-body-style:
    - ESLint will throw an error if the function body is multiline yet has a one-line return on it.
  * @typescript-eslint/ban-ts-comment:
    - The typescript-eslint now bans @ts-<directive> comments from being used
  * @typescript-eslint/naming-convention:
    - typescript-eslint does not enforce uppercase for const only.
  * no-redeclare:
    - ESLint does not support check-parameters.
  * import/no-unassigned-import:
    - ESLint's import/no-unassigned-import now accepts a glob pattern for ignores; you'll need to manually convert your ignore-module settings.
  * no-invalid-this:
    - Functions in methods will no longer be ignored.
  * @typescript-eslint/no-unused-expressions:
    - The TSLint optional config "allow-new" is the default ESLint behavior and will no longer be ignored.
  * @typescript-eslint/no-unused-vars:
    - Please read the following article as the rule behaviour may change on the short term: https://github.com/typescript-eslint/typescript-eslint/issues/1856
  * one-var:
    - Variables declared in for loops will no longer be checked.
  * class-methods-use-this:
    - allow-public methods will no longer be ignored.
  * @typescript-eslint/quotes:
    - Option "avoid-template" is not supported by ESLint.
  * space-before-function-paren:
    - Option "constructor" is not supported by ESLint.
    - Option "method" is not supported by ESLint.
  * @typescript-eslint/strict-boolean-expressions:
    - String, number, enum, and mixed union types are now forbidden.
  * eqeqeq:
    - Option "smart" allows for comparing two literal values, evaluating the value of typeof and null comparisons.
  * no-underscore-dangle:
    - Leading and trailing underscores (_) on identifiers will now be ignored.

